[4] South Korea, response of public - media report 3 Jun 2015
Date: 3 Jun 2015
Source: NY Times
http://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/04/world/asia/south-korea-mers-cases-lead-schools-to-close.html?_r=1


Fear of MERS Virus Leads Over 230 South Korean Schools to Close
------------------------
More than 230 schools in South Korea have temporarily shut down, officials said on Wednesday [3 Jun 2015[, as fears of Middle East respiratory syndrome spread through the country.

30 South Koreans have tested positive for the virus that causes the disease, which has killed hundreds of people in 25 countries, mostly in Saudi Arabia. The outbreak in South Korea is the largest reported outside the Middle East, where the virus first emerged in 2012 and where a vast majority of the more than 1100 cases and over 470 deaths reported have occurred.

Two of the South Korean patients died on Monday [1 Jun 2015], and 3 others were in critical condition, health officials said on Wednesday [3 Jun 2015]. The authorities were also awaiting test results for 99 people suspected of being infected. The number of people isolated at home or in state-run quarantine centers while officials monitored them for symptoms had risen to 1364 from 790 a day earlier.

So far in South Korea, all the reported cases of the syndrome, known as MERS, were found among medical staff members, patients or visitors at 5 hospitals. But the school closings were just one demonstration of a widespread public suspicion about the government's response to the situation.

The South Korean education minister, Hwang Yoo-Wea, announced class cancellations and precautionary measures after the virus killed 2 [people]. "A lot of fear we see now is rooted in the distrust of the government and what it says," said Yu Min-yeong, head of Acase, a crisis management consulting firm based in Seoul.

The World Health Organization said on Wednesday [3 Jun 2015] that although a large outbreak outside the Middle East was a new development, it was not recommending any screening procedures at South Korean ports of entry, "or travel or trade restrictions with regard to this event."

In an advisory posted on its website, the organization also said that it expected that additional cases would be reported by the South Korean health authorities, but that "consistent application of adequate infection and prevention and public health measures" has stopped transmission of the disease.

"There is no reason for people to panic, and nothing so far that suggests to me that the virus has changed to become more dangerous," said Dr. Allison McGeer, an expert on infection control at Mount Sinai Hospital in Toronto. Still, as the number of cases grew, alarm increased in South Korea.

Many South Koreans have canceled hospital appointments for fear of infection - a concern critics say was fueled in part by the government's decision not to reveal the names and locations of the 5 hospitals where cases have been discovered. Stores have reported a surge in sales of hand-sanitizing products, which the government recommended as a precaution against the virus. The Defense Ministry has urged men to defer their army reserve training if they suspect MERS symptoms.

As officials have traced the path of the virus in the country, they have found evidence of careless infection control in its public health system. The 1st "index" patient, a 68-year-old employee of an agricultural products company, returned home on [4 May 2015] via Qatar after visiting Bahrain, the United Arab Emirates and Saudi Arabia during the previous 2 weeks.

He developed a fever and cough, both symptoms of MERS, on [11 May 2015] and sought care at 3 clinics. But doctors did not suspect MERS because he did not tell them about his Middle East trip. A doctor and a nurse from those clinics later tested positive for the virus.

It was not until [18 May 2015] that a doctor at a larger hospital asked the government authorities to test the man for the virus. Two days later, he was declared the country's 1st MERS case. Twenty-four other cases have since been traced to that hospital.

One of them, a 44-year-old man who visited his father there, flew to China on [26 May 2015] via Hong Kong, although he had been advised by doctors to stay home. The penalty for ignoring such advice is a fine of up to 3 million won, or USD 2700. He tested positive in China and was quarantined there last week.

Another patient, a 58-year-old woman, was infected through contact with the 1st patient but was released after treatment for asthma. The health authorities did not trace her to another hospital until Sunday [31 May 2015]. She died of MERS on Monday [1 Jun 2015].

"We apologize for the inappropriate initial responses," Moon Hyung-pyo, the minister of health and welfare, said during a news conference on Tuesday. "We were too relaxed."

In yet another case, a 40-year-old man who stayed in the same hospital ward as the 1st patient to get treatment for pneumonia was released after his condition appeared to have improved. Officials traced him to another hospital on Sunday [31 May 2015]. The next day, 2 patients who shared a room with him there tested positive. They were the 1st tertiary, or 3rd-generation, infections reported. Until then, the government had said that such 3rd-generation cases were unlikely.

Government health officials said they had decided not to reveal the names of affected hospitals to prevent a panic surrounding them, a policy even some lawmakers from the governing Saenuri Party have criticized.

On Wednesday [3 Jun 2015], the government offered cash payments to poor people who could not work while they were under government quarantine. The subsidies were announced amid concern that impoverished workers might be reluctant to report contacts with MERS patients for fear of losing their jobs.

The Education Ministry said it was advising schools to consider temporarily closing if they feared a mass infection among students. But during a news briefing on Wednesday [3 Jun 2015], Kwon Jun-wook, a senior Health Ministry official, called the closing of schools "medically wrong." Kim Woo-joo, head of the Korean Society of Infectious Diseases, also opposed the closing of schools, calling it too drastic a precaution.

MERS is caused by a coronavirus from the same family as the one that caused the deadly outbreak in China in 2003 of severe acute respiratory syndrome, or SARS. There is no vaccine. Health officials have said that evidence is mounting that dromedary camels could transmit the virus to humans through close contact.

[Byline: Choe Sang-Hunjune with Rick Gladstone contributed reporting from New York].

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[It is clear that there is panic ongoing in South Korea as this outbreak continues to grow in size. It is unclear why the schools have actually closed for 2 days in the absence of cases in the schools, unless this is a reaction to contact tracing that may have identified individuals in the school system. Unfortunately there are often political reactions to emergency situations that are not always grounded in science, as has been seen with a number of outbreaks in recent years.

It does not appear that this outbreak is different than other nosocomial outbreaks of MERS-CoV seen in Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates over the past few years of MERS-CoV activity. The main difference with this outbreak is the real time information provided with details as the outbreak is ongoing, clearly defining the nosocomial transmission in terms of identifying contacts with cases, times of exposures, and locations of exposures (defined as hospital B, D, E, F - to the chagrin of the population in Korea who want to know specifically the names of the hospitals). Ironically, one suspects that the involved/implicated hospitals are probably the "safest" locations to go as they are most likely to have stringent infection control practices in place now. - Mod.MPP]

